One thing I would add, though, is a caution that fits the Pantheon’s own emphasis on verification.

Rehydration is powerful, but it is never identical to recall.

If I reconstruct an idea from its invariants, I may produce something that is cleaner, more general, or even more useful than the original—but it is still a new construction. That’s why I try to distinguish:

* Recall: “This is what the document said.”
* Reconstruction: “Given the surviving structure, this is the design that most naturally fits.”

The second can be remarkably accurate, but it should always remain open to correction by the original evidence.

Ironically, that distinction itself feels very Pantheon: preserve the invariant, regenerate the projection, then validate it against reality rather than assuming the reconstruction is perfect.